"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Ezra chapters 8–10
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-ezra-8-10.py

Ch 8: Return journey — Ezra's caravan gathers at Ahava; fasts instead of requesting
      military escort; twelve offerings for twelve tribes upon arrival.
Ch 9: Ezra's great penitential prayer — corporate confession, grace amid guilt,
      the remnant principle; a type of Christ's high-priestly intercession.
Ch 10: The mixed-marriage reform — covenant renewal through radical separation;
       the book's incomplete ending points beyond itself to the NT resolution.

Key Christological themes: Davidic continuity (8:2), priestly intercession (9:5-15),
remnant grace (9:8-9), radical covenant demands (10:3,10-11), the divine hand enabling
the impossible (8:22,31), and the book's open-ended conclusion awaiting a greater reformer.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

EZRA = {
  "8": {
    "1": "<p>The genealogical list in 8:1-14 documents those who returned with Ezra from Babylon ca. 458 BCE. Lists of this kind serve the same function as Matthew's genealogy (Matt 1:1-17): they assert covenant continuity. The Davidic line did not die in exile; neither did the priestly lines of Phinehas and Ithamar (v2). The return is not simply migration — it is the survival of the covenant people whose genealogical identity matters because a specific descendant (the Messiah) must come from within.</p>",
    "2": "<p><strong>Hattush</strong> from the sons of David is a Davidic descendant accompanying Ezra's return. That a son of David makes this journey is a quiet but deliberate signal: the Davidic promise is still being honored. Every generation that the Davidic line survived in exile kept the Messianic possibility open. Matthew traces Christ's lineage through the Babylonian exile (Matt 1:12-16), showing that exile interrupted but did not extinguish the line. The priestly sons of Phinehas and Ithamar alongside the Davidic descendant foreshadow Christ who holds both offices: eternal priest (Heb 7:24) and Davidic king (Luke 1:32-33).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The returning families are counted by number of males registered. The precision of the census reflects the covenant-community accountability that characterizes Ezra-Nehemiah. Those who belong to Israel are counted; their names and numbers are known to God. Christ's parable of the lost sheep (Luke 15:4-7): each of the hundred is known; the one who is missing is sought. God accounts for his people by name.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Two hundred males with Elihoenai from Pahathmoab. The voluntary return pattern (Ezra 7:13 decreed that 'whoever volunteers' may go) means the returning community is a committed remnant, not the whole nation — a pattern Paul develops in Romans 11:5 ('a remnant, chosen by grace'). The numbers testify to partial but real fulfillment of the restoration promise.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Three hundred males with the son of Jahaziel from Shechaniah. The progressive accumulation of numbers across vv3-14 builds a picture of a significant migration. These specific numbers mattered legally for imperial accountability and theologically as evidence that YHWH's covenant people still existed as a community capable of temple worship.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Fifty males with Ebed son of Jonathan from Adin. The smaller contingents (50, 70, 80) alongside the larger (200, 218, 300) show families of varying sizes all responding to the same call. The diversity of sizes mirrors the NT's principle that the call goes out broadly and the response is varied (Matt 22:14 'many are called but few are chosen'), yet all who come are received.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Seventy males with Jeshaiah from Elam. Elam (modern southwest Iran) was a site of Jewish settlement; returnees from Elam demonstrate the geographic spread of the Diaspora. The gathering from multiple dispersed locations anticipates the eschatological gathering (Isa 11:11-12 mentions Elam among the nations from which Israel will be regathered).</p>",
    "8": "<p>Eighty males with Zebadiah from Shephatiah. The list continues the enumeration. Christ's care for his disciples by name: 'He calls his own sheep by name and leads them out' (John 10:3). The covenant community is not an anonymous mass but a counted, named people known to their shepherd.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Two hundred and eighteen males with Obadiah from Joab. One of the largest contingents. The preservation of specific family-names across this list witnesses to the scribal tradition Ezra embodies (7:10) — genealogical registers maintained through generations of exile become, ultimately, the raw material for Matthew and Luke's genealogies of Jesus.</p>",
    "10": "<p>One hundred and sixty males from Shelomith/Josiphiah. The accumulating names witness to God's faithfulness: despite 70+ years of exile, distinct family lines remained identifiable and covenant-conscious. This is the remnant-preservation principle — God keeps a people for himself through the darkest periods (cf. 1 Kgs 19:18 'I have kept for myself seven thousand').</p>",
    "11": "<p>Twenty-eight males from Bebai. The smaller contingents matter as much as the larger: every family that returned contributed to the restored community. Christ's principle that the one lost sheep matters as much as the ninety-nine (Luke 15:4) applies: twenty-eight returning males from Bebai are as significant to the covenant as the two hundred from Joab.</p>",
    "12": "<p>One hundred and ten males with Johanan from Azgad. The return draws from across the tribal spectrum, reconstituting something of the twelve-tribe unity symbolically. This partial reconstitution anticipates Christ's choosing twelve apostles as a symbolic new twelve-tribe people of God (Matt 19:28 'you who have followed me will also sit on twelve thrones, judging the twelve tribes of Israel').</p>",
    "13": "<p>Sixty males from the later sons of Adonikam — latecomers to the return. The inclusion of those who came later reflects the grace of the open invitation: the door was available for whoever would come. Christ's parable of the workers hired at different hours (Matt 20:1-16) operates on the same principle: those who come later receive the same grace as those who came first.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Seventy males from Bigvai concludes the list at 14 family groups. That a second major return was possible 80 years after Zerubbabel's demonstrates the sustained hope of Diaspora Jews for restoration — a hope grounded in covenant promises that Christ ultimately fulfills by gathering the scattered children of God (John 11:52).</p>",
    "15": "<p>At the Ahava canal Ezra discovers that no Levites are present among the returnees. The absence of those designated for temple service would leave the restored community without legitimate worship infrastructure. The 'three days' of camping frames the moment as a liminal pause before decisive action. The gap in the community's worship capacity is addressed immediately — Ezra cannot proceed without complete covenant infrastructure, just as Christ's body needs all its gifted members (1 Cor 12:14-21).</p>",
    "16": "<p>Eleven leading men are sent to recruit Levites from Casiphia. The deliberate, organized effort to obtain worship leaders reflects the principle Christ articulates: the harvest is plentiful but workers are few; the solution is to pray and send (Luke 10:1-2). Kingdom work requires intentional deployment of people.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Instructions to Iddo at Casiphia: bring 'ministers for the house of God.' Ezra's authority to mobilize settled Diaspora Levites models the principle that YHWH calls people out of settled comfort for his house — a pattern Christ intensifies in his calls to leave everything and follow (Mark 1:17-20; Luke 9:57-62).</p>",
    "18": "<p><strong>yad ʾĕlōhênû haṭṭôḇāh ʿālênû</strong> — 'By the good hand of our God upon us.' The successful recruitment of Levites is attributed directly to divine provision. Sherebiah is 'a man of good judgment' — human wisdom is the vehicle of the divine hand. Christ is the one in whom are hidden 'all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge' (Col 2:3); his hand equips his servants for the work he assigns them.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Hashabiah and Jeshaiah from the sons of Merari with twenty brothers and sons. The Merarite Levites carried the heavy frames of the tabernacle (Num 3:36-37). Their presence connects the restored community to the wilderness-period worship structure. The specific tribal assignments to worship service were covenantal; their resumption signals genuine restoration of the Mosaic order.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Two hundred and twenty Nethinim — 'given ones' appointed by David. The Nethinim were likely descendants of conquered peoples incorporated into temple service (Josh 9:27 Gibeonites). Their inclusion in Ezra's return demonstrates that covenant community membership is not purely ethnic: foreigners 'given to' YHWH's service belong in the restored community. This anticipates the NT's inclusion of Gentiles in the people of God (Eph 2:19 'no longer foreigners and strangers but fellow citizens').</p>",
    "21": "<p><strong>ləhitkannōt lipnê ʾĕlōhênû</strong> — 'so that we might humble ourselves before our God.' Ezra calls a fast for explicit theological purposes: humility and seeking God for a safe journey. Ezra's fasting anticipates Christ's forty-day fast (Matt 4:1-2) and his instruction that certain things come only through prayer and fasting (Matt 17:21). Corporate fasting is a covenantal act — the community submits to God rather than relying on Persian military protection.</p>",
    "22": "<p><strong>kî-yad ʾĕlōhênû ʿal-kol-mébaqšāyw ləṭôḇāh</strong> — 'The hand of God is upon all who seek him for good.' Ezra's public theological claim creates a test: if he asks for troops and the journey fails, YHWH is discredited; if he trusts without troops and arrives safely, YHWH is glorified. This is the logic of faith: trusting God's stated provision at the cost of visible means of protection. Christ embodies this fully — he could have called twelve legions of angels (Matt 26:53) but chose not to. Vulnerability becomes the vehicle of divine demonstration.</p>",
    "23": "<p><strong>wayyēʿāter lānû</strong> — 'he answered our prayer' (lit. 'allowed himself to be entreated'). The niphal of <em>ʿātar</em> (to allow oneself to be moved) occurs at key moments of divine responsiveness: Gen 25:21 (Isaac's prayer), 2 Chr 33:13 (Manasseh's prayer). Prayer works because God is genuinely responsive. Heb 4:16 grounds this in Christ: 'approach the throne of grace with confidence, so that we may receive mercy and find grace to help in time of need.'</p>",
    "24": "<p>Twelve leading priests are set apart to guard the treasure — one per tribe for a mission concerning all Israel. The appointment of specific, accountable individuals for the care of sacred things reflects the priestly principle of stewardship. Christ entrusts the gospel to specific people ('you are my witnesses,' Acts 1:8) and holds them accountable for how they steward it (Matt 25:19-21).</p>",
    "25": "<p>The enormous wealth — contributed by the king, his counselors, and the whole Jewish community — is precisely weighed before the priests. The precision of sacred accounting models the principle that those who handle what belongs to God must do so with complete transparency. Paul: 'We are taking pains to do what is right, not only in the eyes of the Lord but also in the eyes of man' (2 Cor 8:20-21).</p>",
    "26": "<p>Six hundred and fifty talents of silver (approximately 24 metric tons), one hundred silver vessels, one hundred talents of gold. That such wealth was entrusted to twelve priests traveling without military escort is the practical expression of v22's faith principle. The wealth is protected not by arms but by the hand of the God who owns it (Hag 2:8 'the silver is mine and the gold is mine'). Christ sends his disciples 'without purse or bag' (Luke 22:35) on the same trust principle.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Twenty gold bowls and two exceptional bronze vessels valued 'as precious as gold.' The principle: nothing substandard is brought into God's house. The giving of one's best to God runs throughout Scripture: Abel's fat portions (Gen 4:4), the tithe of firstfruits (Deut 26:2), and ultimately Christ's self-offering as the perfect, unblemished sacrifice (Heb 9:14 'offered himself unblemished to God').</p>",
    "28": "<p><strong>ʾattem qōdeš la-YHWH wəhaḵēlîm qōdeš</strong> — 'You are consecrated to the LORD, and these vessels are consecrated.' <em>Qōdeš la-YHWH</em> ('Holy to the LORD') is the inscription on the High Priest's golden headband (Exod 28:36). Ezra applies it to the escorting priests. The NT extends this: all believers are 'a holy priesthood' (1 Pet 2:5), their bodies 'temples of the Holy Spirit' (1 Cor 6:19-20), consecrated not by a gold plate but by Christ's atoning work.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Guard the treasure until weighed out in Jerusalem 'before the leading priests, Levites, and family heads.' The complete chain of accountability — weighed going in, weighed on arrival — reflects the principle that sacred trust requires verifiable faithfulness. Paul grounds this in eschatology: each steward's work will be revealed and tested (1 Cor 4:1-5; 2 Cor 5:10).</p>",
    "30": "<p>The priests and Levites receive the weighed amounts and take personal accountability for the temple treasure. The act of receiving is an act of covenant responsibility. The same logic applies to the gospel entrusted to the church: 'Guard the good deposit that was entrusted to you — guard it with the help of the Holy Spirit' (2 Tim 1:14).</p>",
    "31": "<p><strong>yad ʾĕlōhênû ʿālênû wayyaṣṣîlênû mikkap ʾôyēḇ</strong> — 'the hand of our God was upon us and delivered us from enemy ambush.' The journey through the Syrian desert was genuinely dangerous — the company arrived safely with enormous wealth but no military escort. The 'good hand of God' (fifth occurrence in Ezra 7-8) vindicates Ezra's faith statement in v22. Christ's promise to his sent-out disciples: 'I am sending you out like lambs among wolves' (Luke 10:3) — vulnerable by design, protected by the divine hand.</p>",
    "32": "<p>'We arrived in Jerusalem and stayed three days.' The three-day rest recalls the three-day pattern of covenant encounters throughout Scripture (Exod 19:16; Josh 1:11; Jon 1:17). Rest precedes sacred activity. The resurrection narrative's 'on the third day' (1 Cor 15:4) is the ultimate three-day fulfillment — after the journey through death, the presentation of the ultimate sacrifice before God.</p>",
    "33": "<p>The treasure is formally weighed on the fourth day in God's house, with two Levites as witnesses. The precision — number, weight, full total recorded — models the complete accountability with which the sacred is handled. The integrity of the accounting process is itself a form of worship. Christ commends the faithful steward who gives a full accounting (Matt 25:20-21).</p>",
    "34": "<p>'Everything was accounted for by number and by weight; the full total was recorded at that time.' The completeness of the accounting marks successful transfer. Christ's 'it is finished' (John 19:30) is the ultimate completed accounting — the full atoning work accomplished, nothing lacking. The heavenly record (Rev 20:12 'the books were opened') is the eschatological counterpart to Ezra's temple archive.</p>",
    "35": "<p><strong>pārîm šənêm-ʿāśār ʿal-kol-yiśrāʾēl</strong> — 'twelve bulls as burnt offerings for all Israel.' The twelve-bull offering for twelve tribes (as at 6:17) is a covenant-renewal act: the returning exiles represent and intercede for the whole of Israel. This intercessory dimension anticipates Christ's high-priestly prayer 'not only for these, but also for those who will believe through their message' (John 17:20) — an intercession reaching beyond the immediate community to all God's people.</p>",
    "36": "<p>The king's orders are presented to the Persian satraps, who provide support for the people and temple. The chapter ends with imperial cooperation in restoration. The pattern throughout Ezra: YHWH works through pagan rulers to accomplish redemptive purposes — Cyrus, Darius, Artaxerxes all serve as instruments. 'The king's heart is a stream of water in the LORD's hand' (Prov 21:1). Christ's lordship over all rulers (Matt 28:18 'all authority in heaven and on earth') brings this principle to its ultimate expression.</p>"
  },
  "9": {
    "1": "<p>The intermarriage crisis is reported to Ezra immediately after the successful journey. The listing of peoples — Canaanites, Hittites, Perizzites, Jebusites, Ammonites, Moabites, Egyptians, Amorites — echoes the Deuteronomic list of forbidden intermarriage partners (Deut 7:1-4). The reference to 'the holy offspring' (<em>zeraʿ haqqōdeš</em>) being mixed with foreign peoples frames the problem in genealogical-covenantal terms: the line of promise is being compromised. Christ resolves this not by ethnic separation but by transforming what 'holy seed' means — the new covenant community is Spirit-born, not genealogically defined (John 1:12-13; 3:5-6).</p>",
    "2": "<p><strong>zeraʿ haqqōdeš</strong> — 'the holy seed/offspring.' <em>Zeraʿ</em> (H2233) is the word of Gen 3:15 (seed of the woman), Gen 12:7 (Abraham's seed), and Gal 3:16 (Paul's argument that the singular 'seed' = Christ). The 'mixing' of the holy seed with foreign peoples threatens the genealogical integrity from which the promised Seed must come. Christ is the one in whom all the nations are blessed (Gen 22:18; Gal 3:8) — the Seed who ends the need for ethnic separation by becoming the meeting point of all peoples.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Ezra's physical response — tearing garment and robe, pulling out head and beard hair, sitting in shock — is the most extreme expression of mourning in the OT. The intensity of Ezra's grief is proportional to the gravity of the covenant breach. He does not rebuke or punish; he mourns representatively before God. This intercessory grief anticipates Christ's weeping over Jerusalem (Luke 19:41-44) and the Spirit's 'groaning' in intercession (Rom 8:26-27) — the righteous one bearing the burden of others' sin.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'All who trembled at the words of the God of Israel' gathered around Ezra. <em>Ḥārēḏ</em> (H2730, to tremble) is the term in Isa 66:2 for the person YHWH esteems: 'humble, contrite in spirit, and trembling at my word.' The gathering of the God-fearers around the mourning intercessor forms a penitential assembly. The same principle operates in the NT church: bearing one another's burdens (Gal 6:2), weeping with those who weep (Rom 12:15).</p>",
    "5": "<p>At the evening offering (<em>minḥat hāʿereḇ</em>) Ezra rises from prostration and falls on his knees with hands spread out — the classic posture of petition (cf. 1 Kgs 8:54 Solomon's prayer). The timing aligns his prayer with the daily tamid offering. Christ, the ultimate evening sacrifice (Heb 9:26 'once at the end of the ages he has appeared'), transforms this pattern: his offering makes all subsequent intercession possible (Heb 7:25 'he always lives to intercede for them').</p>",
    "7": "<p>'From the days of our ancestors to this very day we have been deeply guilty.' Ezra prays in the first-person plural — 'we,' 'our,' 'us' — though he was not personally guilty. This is representative, corporate confession. Daniel (Dan 9:5-19) and Nehemiah (Neh 1:6-7) use the same posture. Christ takes corporate identification to its ultimate degree: 'God made him who had no sin to be sin for us' (2 Cor 5:21) — complete representative identification with the guilty community, far beyond what Ezra could achieve.</p>",
    "8": "<p><strong>wəʿattāh kimʿaṭ-rāgaʿ hāytāh ḥinnāh mēʾet YHWH ʾĕlōhênû</strong> — 'But now for a brief moment grace has been shown us by the LORD our God, who has left us a surviving remnant (<em>pəlêṭāh</em>).' The pivot from extended confession to hope rests on a single word: <em>ḥinnāh</em> (grace, H2580). Grace is the exception that overrides the logic of deserved judgment. Paul unpacks this as the operative principle of the new covenant: 'a remnant chosen by grace' (Rom 11:5), 'and if by grace, then it cannot be based on works' (Rom 11:6). Grace is the precise theological category that makes the remnant's existence explicable.</p>",
    "9": "<p><strong>kî ʿăḇāḏîm ʾănaḥnû wəḇəʿaḇdûṯênû lōʾ-ʿăzāḇānû ʾĕlōhênû</strong> — 'Though we are slaves, our God has not abandoned us in our captivity, but has extended his steadfast love (<em>ḥeseḏ</em>) to us.' YHWH's <em>ḥeseḏ</em> is not negated by the community's unfaithfulness or political subordination. This is the ground of all NT hope: 'If we are faithless, he remains faithful, for he cannot deny himself' (2 Tim 2:13). Christ's death is the ultimate expression of <em>ḥeseḏ</em> toward a faithless people (Rom 5:8 'while we were still sinners, Christ died for us').</p>",
    "10": "<p>'And now, our God, what can we say after all this?' The rhetorical despair acknowledges that the community has no legal standing before God. All arguments for leniency have been exhausted; the only recourse is to throw oneself on mercy. This is the posture Christ describes in the parable of the Pharisee and tax collector: 'God, have mercy on me, a sinner' (Luke 18:13) — not attempting to establish merit but pleading for grace. The inability to speak in self-defense before a holy God is the beginning of true repentance.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Ezra incorporates the prophetic prohibition directly into his prayer (Deut 7:1-4; Lev 18:24-28). Prayer formed by Scripture aligns with God's revealed will. The model: Jesus quoting Scripture as the authoritative basis for prayer and discernment ('It is written…' Matt 4:4,7,10) — the Word of God is the grammar of prayer.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The Deuteronomic intermarriage prohibition quoted: 'do not give your daughters to their sons or take their daughters for your sons.' The prohibition was not ethnic exclusivism but theological protectionism — intermarriage with idol-worshipers leads to worship of their gods (1 Kgs 11:1-8). The deeper principle is retained in the NT while the ethnic form is transformed: 'Do not be unequally yoked with unbelievers' (2 Cor 6:14), now defined by spiritual allegiance, not genealogy.</p>",
    "13": "<p><strong>ḥāśaḵtāh lammattāḥ mēʿāwōnênû</strong> — 'you have punished us less than our iniquities deserve.' The confession that partial judgment is itself mercy. The exile was deserved; its ending was grace. The full measure of deserved punishment was not executed. The NT's answer to why: the punishment was not canceled but deferred, so that it could be concentrated on Christ at the cross — the one who bore 'the full measure' so that his people receive the merciful portion (2 Cor 5:21; Rom 8:3-4).</p>",
    "14": "<p>'Shall we again break your commands and intermarry with peoples who commit these abominations? Would you not be so angry as to consume us without remnant?' The rhetorical question expects 'yes' — YHWH would be fully justified in total judgment. The community's only hope is that he will not exercise his full rights. The gospel is the answer: in Christ, full justice is executed (Rom 3:25-26) and full mercy extended simultaneously — 'both just and the justifier of the one who has faith in Jesus.'</p>",
    "15": "<p><strong>YHWH ʾĕlōhê yiśrāʾēl ṣaddîq ʾāttāh</strong> — 'O LORD God of Israel, you are righteous; here we are before you in our guilt.' The prayer ends with divine righteousness and human guilt standing in tension, without resolution. Paul takes this as the starting point of his gospel argument: 'all have sinned' + 'God is righteous' → the only resolution is the righteousness of God displayed in Christ's atoning death, justifying the ungodly without compromising divine justice (Rom 3:26).</p>"
  },
  "10": {
    "1": "<p>Ezra's prayer and tears draw 'a very large assembly.' The communal repentance triggered by one person's intercessory grief is a recurring biblical pattern (Joel 2:12-13; Jonah 3:5-10). Christ's own weeping over Jerusalem (Luke 19:41) and his prayer in Gethsemane (Heb 5:7 'offered prayers with loud crying and tears') are the ultimate expression of intercessory sorrow that draws others into repentance.</p>",
    "2": "<p><strong>māʿalnû ḇêʾlōhênû</strong> — 'we have been unfaithful to our God.' Shechaniah names the specific sin plainly using the same key verb <em>māʿal</em> (H4603, unfaithfulness/trespass) that Ezra used in 9:2,4. Confession that names the specific sin is the necessary first step of covenant restoration (Lev 26:40-41; 1 John 1:9 'if we confess our sins, he is faithful and just and will forgive us our sins').</p>",
    "3": "<p><strong>niqrāt-bərît lêʾlōhênû</strong> — 'let us make a covenant with our God.' The response to covenant breach is covenant renewal — Sinai after the golden calf (Exod 34), the Josianic renewal (2 Kgs 23:1-3), the Nehemiah covenant (Neh 9-10). The covenant to 'send away all these foreign wives' is radically costly — dissolving marriages. Christ's language is equally costly: 'If your right eye causes you to sin, gouge it out… it is better to lose one part than for your whole body to be thrown into hell' (Matt 5:29). The seriousness of covenant demands has not diminished in the new covenant.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'Rise up, for this task is yours to lead, and we are with you.' The community delegates execution to Ezra but commits to support him. The combination of strong leader and committed community mirrors the NT's theology of authority and cooperation: Christ is the head (Eph 1:22) but the whole body is required for the body to function (Eph 4:15-16).</p>",
    "5": "<p>Ezra puts the leading priests, Levites, and all Israel under oath to carry out the covenant. The oath invokes YHWH as binding authority. Christ raises the standard above oath-taking to integrity itself: 'let your yes be yes and your no be no' (Matt 5:37), fulfilling the oath-covenant pattern by making the community's word as binding as an oath through transformed character.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Ezra fasts throughout the night in Jehohanan's room — 'for he was mourning the unfaithfulness of the exiles.' Leadership bears the weight of the community's sin even after the community has responded. Moses fasted forty days interceding for Israel after the golden calf (Exod 34:28; Deut 9:18-19). Christ's high-priestly intercession is continuous and permanent (Heb 7:25 'he always lives to intercede for them').</p>",
    "7": "<p>A proclamation is sent throughout Judah and Jerusalem requiring all returned exiles to gather in three days. Urgency and universal scope — an imperial-style call to covenant assembly. The NT equivalent: the proclamation of the gospel requiring response (Mark 1:15 'repent and believe the good news'; Acts 17:30 'God commands all people everywhere to repent').</p>",
    "8": "<p>The penalty for non-appearance: confiscation of property and expulsion from the community. The severity reflects the crisis level of the covenant breach. The NT has analogous community discipline (Matt 18:17; 1 Cor 5:1-5), though the purpose is restorative ('hand this man over to Satan, so that the sinful nature may be destroyed and his spirit saved,' 1 Cor 5:5). The goal is covenant fidelity, not punishment for its own sake.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The whole assembly gathers in the ninth month (Kislev, November-December), in heavy rain, <em>ḥărādîm</em> — 'trembling.' The <em>ḥārad</em> root is the same as in Isa 66:2: 'this is the one I esteem: the humble and contrite in spirit, and who trembles at my word.' The seriousness of standing before God's covenant claim is physically felt. Christ himself trembled greatly (<em>ekthambeisthai</em>) in Gethsemane (Mark 14:33) — solidarity with human fear before the divine demand.</p>",
    "10": "<p><strong>ʾattem məʿaltem ûṯôšiḇû nāšîm nokəriyyôt</strong> — 'You have been unfaithful — you have married foreign women, adding to Israel's guilt.' Ezra's direct accusation names both the act and its theological category. The directness of confronting sin is modeled throughout Scripture: Nathan to David (2 Sam 12:7), Jesus to the churches (Rev 2-3). Loving directness — naming sin plainly rather than managing it diplomatically — is a form of pastoral care.</p>",
    "11": "<p><strong>hipparaḏû mēʿammê hāʾāreṣ</strong> — 'Separate yourselves from the peoples of the land.' The covenant community's holiness requires distinction from surrounding practices. The NT transforms but retains the separation principle: 'come out from them and be separate' (2 Cor 6:17, quoting Isa 52:11) — separation from sinful patterns, not from persons. Christ ate with sinners (Mark 2:15-17) while remaining distinct from sin; his followers are in the world but not of it (John 17:14-16).</p>",
    "12": "<p>'Yes! We must do exactly as you have said.' The whole assembly's loud, unified assent — one of the high points of the book. The NT parallel: the Pentecost response, 'What shall we do?' (Acts 2:37), leading to immediate repentance and baptism. Readiness to obey what is costly and public is the sign of genuine repentance rather than mere remorse.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The practical complications: too many people, the rainy season, no one can stand outside long. A structured process is proposed. The acknowledgment of practical constraints in carrying out a covenant obligation is not unspiritual — it is wise stewardship of available means. Paul's principle: 'Let all things be done decently and in order' (1 Cor 14:40) applies to covenant reform as much as to worship.</p>",
    "14": "<p>A fair process is established: representatives per city, individual appointments, each case heard at set times. Justice requires both decisiveness (the matter must be addressed) and fairness (each case must be heard). Christ's warnings against hasty judgment (Matt 7:1-5) and his commitment to just judgment (John 5:30) hold these in tension.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Only two men (and two supporting Levites) opposed the plan. The minority objection is noted — the community's decision was not unanimous. The recording of dissent is honest historiography: covenant renewal is rarely without opposition. Christ encountered opponents in every crowd; the early church faced opposition from within (Acts 15:1-2). Faithful reform proceeds despite opposition.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The review process takes three months — from the twentieth of the ninth month (v9) to the first of the first month (v17). The thoroughness reflects the gravity of the matter: each case individually reviewed. Patience required for thorough reform (rather than hasty resolution) is itself a form of covenant faithfulness. Christ's three-year ministry and the Spirit's ongoing sanctification (Phil 1:6) operate on the same principle.</p>",
    "17": "<p>By the first of Nisan the review is complete. Nisan is the month of Passover — the founding redemptive event. Completing the reform at the threshold of Passover season connects covenant renewal to its foundational celebration. In Christ, every day is Passover fulfillment (1 Cor 5:7 'Christ, our Passover lamb, has been sacrificed').</p>",
    "18": "<p>The list of offenders begins with the priests — the most serious category. Joshua son of Jozadak's sons are among the guilty; that the high-priestly family is implicated testifies to the depth of the problem. No class is exempt from covenant demands. The NT principle of judgment 'beginning with God's household' (1 Pet 4:17) echoes this: accountability starts at the top.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'They pledged to put away their foreign wives; and acknowledging their guilt, they brought a ram as a guilt offering.' The guilt offering (<em>ʾāšām</em>, H817) accompanies confession: the formal reparation for covenant trespass. Christ is the ultimate <em>ʾāšām</em> (Isa 53:10 'when you make his life a guilt offering'); his sacrifice makes all subsequent guilt offerings unnecessary (Heb 10:12-14 'one sacrifice for sins, once and for all').</p>",
    "20": "<p>Two priests from the sons of Immer. The list continues methodically — no tribe, no family, no individual is omitted for communal comfort. The willingness to name specific offenders publicly is the price of genuine covenant accountability. The NT church's responsibility to name sin within the community (1 Cor 5:1-5; Gal 2:11-14) operates on the same principle.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Five priests from the sons of Harim. The accumulation of names across vv18-44 reinforces that the problem was widespread — systemic, not isolated. The breadth of the failure is itself a form of confessional honesty: the community does not minimize the scale of the breach by recording only a few representative cases.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Six priests from the sons of Pashur. Prominent families held accountable to the same standard as others models the covenant principle that there is 'no partiality with God' (Rom 2:11). The gospel's demand applies equally to the prominent and the obscure.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Six Levites named among the offenders. Those appointed to guard the holiness of the sanctuary had themselves become covenant-compromised — the irony deepens with each priestly/Levitical name. The NT parallel: teachers and elders are held to stricter judgment precisely because their role is to model covenant faithfulness (Jas 3:1).</p>",
    "24": "<p>One singer (Eliashib) and three gatekeepers. Even the singers and doorkeepers of the sanctuary are implicated. The universality of sin across all temple-service categories ('all have sinned,' Rom 3:23) is matched by the universality of the demanded response: 'all people everywhere to repent' (Acts 17:30).</p>",
    "25": "<p>The lay Israelites begin with the sons of Parosh. The transition from temple personnel to lay people expands the list to the whole community. The reform is not merely institutional but social — the whole people must maintain covenant integrity. Christ's demand reaches into every sphere of life, not only religious practice (Matt 22:37-40).</p>",
    "26": "<p>Six men from the sons of Elam. The sons of Elam appear in the genealogy of returnees (8:7) and here in the offenders' list — the same family contributes to both covenant restoration and covenant crisis. No family group is uniformly righteous; faithful and faithless exist side by side (Matt 13:24-30 'wheat and weeds growing together'). The final separation awaits the harvest.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Six men from the sons of Zattu. The repetitive structure of the list is almost liturgical in its thoroughness. The tedium of reading mirrors the tedium of reform: genuine covenant renewal is not dramatic moments but patient, case-by-case accountability — the Spirit's sanctifying work 'from glory to glory' (2 Cor 3:18), not in a single moment.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Four men from the sons of Bebai. The same family appears in the return list (8:11) and here in the offenders' list. The people who made the costly journey from Babylon were susceptible to the same compromises as those who never left. Return from exile did not guarantee spiritual transformation — a truth that only the new birth (John 3:3-8) and the indwelling Spirit (Ezek 36:26-27) can ultimately address.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Seven men from the sons of Bani. The Bani family produces the largest single contingent of offenders in the lay list. The scale of a community's exposure to a temptation correlates with the scale of its failures — when covenant compromise becomes normalized within a social circle, it spreads through that network: 'A little yeast works through the whole batch' (1 Cor 5:6).</p>",
    "30": "<p>Eight men from the sons of Pahathmoab. The name 'Pahathmoab' (governor of Moab) hints at mixed origins — possibly a family with historical Moabite connections. Ruth the Moabite was a model convert who chose YHWH wholeheartedly (Ruth 1:16); her descendants are among those now compromising that fidelity. Christ descends from Ruth (Matt 1:5) — the Gentile woman who chose covenant faithfulness is in the line of the one who makes covenant faithfulness possible for all.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Sons of Harim continue the list. The grinding detail communicates what narrative cannot: the scale of the crisis, the thoroughness of the investigation, the community's willingness to face its failure without abbreviation. The NT equivalent: the searching self-examination Paul calls for, 'Examine yourselves to see whether you are in the faith; test yourselves' (2 Cor 13:5) — not a cursory glance but a thorough accounting.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Benjamin, Malluch, and Shemariah from the sons of Harim. That the tribe of Benjamin (Paul's own tribe, Phil 3:5) is represented among the offenders is a reminder that no tribal or family heritage provides automatic covenant standing. Christ's confrontation with those who claimed Abrahamic descent (John 8:37-44): ancestry does not confer righteousness.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Seven men from the sons of Hashum. The methodical listing continues, family by family. Quick resolutions that avoid individual accountability produce the appearance of reform without substance. The Spirit's sanctifying work in the individual believer operates with similar thoroughness — a lifelong process (Heb 12:1-2 'let us run with perseverance').</p>",
    "34": "<p>Sons of Bani begin a sub-list that continues across vv34-42. The Bani family's offenders require multiple verses, indicating how deeply the problem was embedded in this particular clan. Communities where covenant compromise becomes normalized require more extensive reformation than those where it remains exceptional.</p>",
    "35": "<p>Names continue: Bedeiah, Chelluh, Vaniah. Each name represents a family disrupted, a marriage dissolved, children separated. The book does not sentimentalize: the covenant demand is honored at real human cost. Christ's own words are honest about this: 'I have not come to bring peace but a sword… to turn a man against his father' (Matt 10:34-36, quoting Mic 7:6).</p>",
    "36": "<p>Meremoth, Eliashib — the same name Meremoth appears in 8:33 as the priest who received the temple treasure. Whether the same individual or a namesake, the coincidence highlights the intersection of faithful stewardship and personal sin within the same community. Human complexity defies simple categories; the same person can be both faithful in one area and compromised in another.</p>",
    "37": "<p>Mattenai, Mattaniah, Jaasau from the sons of Bani. As the list approaches its end, the accumulation of names has achieved its rhetorical purpose: demonstrating that the reform was thorough, documented, and applied without favoritism. The community that can name its failures honestly is positioned for genuine restoration.</p>",
    "38": "<p>Binnui, Shimei. The list of Bani's sons continues. The depth of one family's entanglement with covenant compromise warns about the power of community norms: when intermarriage becomes acceptable within a social circle, it spreads through that network. The individual choice is always embedded in a community context that either supports or undermines covenant faithfulness.</p>",
    "39": "<p>Shelemiah, Nathan, Adaiah. The name Nathan recalls the prophet who confronted David's sin — here a descendant of his era carries a compromised covenant standing. The juxtaposition: the descendant of prophetic confrontation himself requires confrontation. No name or heritage insulates against the need for ongoing covenant accountability.</p>",
    "40": "<p>Machnadebai, Shashai, Sharai — among the sons of Bani. The names here are not found elsewhere in Scripture, reflecting ordinary, non-famous members of the community. That their names are preserved in the canonical text is itself a statement: each covenant member matters. 'Are not five sparrows sold for two pennies? Yet not one of them is forgotten by God' (Luke 12:6).</p>",
    "41": "<p>Azareel, Shelemiah, Shemariah. The tail end of the Bani sub-list. The Bible's unflinching honesty about Israel's sin is one of the strongest arguments for its authenticity — a self-serving propaganda document would not preserve this material. The willingness to document failure is itself a form of integrity.</p>",
    "42": "<p>Shallum, Amariah, and Joseph complete the Bani sub-list. After the great intercessory prayer of ch. 9 and the covenant-renewal drama of ch. 10:1-17, the chapter ends in a list of names — a deliberately understated conclusion to a book that began with the dramatic decree of Cyrus. The work of reform is administrative and relational as much as spiritual.</p>",
    "43": "<p>From the sons of Nebo: seven men. Nebo was a Babylonian city and the name of the Babylonian god of wisdom — Jewish families in Babylon sometimes carried names with pagan associations. Jews from 'Nebo' among both the returnees and the offenders illustrates how deep Babylonian cultural influence had penetrated. Cultural assimilation was the soil in which covenant compromise grew — a dynamic Christ addresses when he warns against the world's values infiltrating the community (John 17:15-17).</p>",
    "44": "<p>'All of these had married foreign women; and some of the women had already borne children.' The final verse is the saddest in the book — children exist from these marriages, meaning dissolution involved already-formed families. The book ends without resolution: what happened to the women and children? Ezra does not say. The restoration community is purified but the human cost is unresolved. Ezra points beyond itself to a greater resolution — one who takes Gentiles not out of the covenant community but fully into it (Eph 2:19; Rev 21:24-26), and whose atonement covers the full human cost of sin rather than distributing it among the innocent. The open ending of Ezra is answered only in the gospel.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'ezra')
    merge_comm(c, EZRA)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'ezra', c)
    count = sum(len(v) for v in EZRA.values())
    print(f'ezra mkt-christ: wrote {count} verses for ch 8-10')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
